name: NPR
text: Breaking: A federal judge has temporarily blocked President Trump's TikTok ban, granting a temporary reprieve to the wildly popular video-sharing app. https://t.co/7LTd4TebcB

name: NPR
text:
States have claimed for decades that lethal injection is quick, peaceful and painless. But an NPR review of more than 200 autopsies showed signs of pulmonary edema, which can induce the feeling of suffocation or drowning, in 84% of cases.
https://t.co/14E6qh0PCf

name: NPR
text:
When it comes to COVID-19 and pregnancy, an OB-GYN says the virus seems to be able to cross the placenta and infect fetuses — but that it "doesn't seem to happen very often."

And, unlike Zika, there isn't evidence of an association with birth defects.
https://t.co/2eKYcnmxQm

name: NPR
text:
Fighting broke out between Armenia and Azerbaijan in the disputed territory of Nagorno-Karabakh on Sunday, causing casualties on both sides and prompting the Armenian government to declare martial law and mobilize its military.
https://t.co/Sv3Fk9bm4I

name: NPR
text: Fire up the DeLorean and don't stress about messing stuff up. https://t.co/5BbEuH348O

name: NPR
text:
Before pursuing music full-time, Mama Haze, aka California songwriter Meaghan Maples, was a doula and caregiver, often prescribing music as an antidote to patients' pain. She says her song "On Your Side" was written during a time of healing.
https://t.co/lfYied73Ef

name: NPR
text:
The icebreaker Polarstern set out from Norway last September and is due back in port in Germany in October. The expedition @MOSAiCArctic is collecting data in the Arctic Ocean to better understand the loss of polar ice and climate change. | @hereandnow
https://t.co/6DNFle52BS

name: NPR
text:
NASA astronaut Kate Rubins is planning to vote from space on Election Day.

"I think it's really important for everybody to vote," Rubins said. "If we can do it from space, then I believe folks can do it from the ground, too."
https://t.co/RXcPEo6Sn4

name: NPR
text: The executive board of the union representing more than 6,400 of New York City's school leaders is calling on Mayor Bill de Blasio to cede control of the city's education department for the duration of the public health crisis. https://t.co/0X4MT7imR6

name: NPR
text:
Ladies, if he:

- just won a gold medal
- saves lives
- has found dozens of explosives and cleared over 1.5 million square feet of land
- loves bananas

He's not your man. He's Magawa, the African giant pouched rat.
https://t.co/NyqKnIAshL

name: NPR
text:
Ja Nelle Pleasure's family used to volunteer at a food pantry, now they depend on it — and they're not the only ones. The number of families struggling to afford food has more than doubled since the pandemic began.
https://t.co/BxA3iIIyXi

name: NPR
text:
Before the pandemic, the number of American families experiencing food insecurity had been steadily falling. But now, as economic instability and a health crisis take over, estimates point to some of the worst rates of food insecurity in the U.S. in years.
https://t.co/9xD2Z2h9Jp

name: NPR
text:
The town of Lexington, Neb., has long struggled with food insecurity. But when the coronavirus hit, it presented new challenges in feeding this community of 11,000 residents.
https://t.co/59Y0G5W8fM

name: NPR
text: Since March, the number of people who lack a steady source of food has grown. In Montgomery County, one of the wealthiest counties in the country, a food assistance effort often runs out of prepared meals before it can feed everyone in need. https://t.co/dgcOXh7ss5
